text:
2. Applications of the Content

2.1 Study Area: Beijing Municipality
I chose Beijing as the study area for this week. Beijing municipality is an ideal case for urban heat analysis: it is a large, dense megacity surrounded by mountainous rural areas, meaning the contrast between hot urban core and cooler periphery is sharp and spatially interpretable. The municipality encompasses both the dense commercial and residential centre and extensive outer districts including mountainous terrain to the north and west.
For administrative boundaries I used GADM 4.1 rather than FAO GAUL, because GAUL Level 2 returns only 2 features for Beijing — insufficient for meaningful per-district analysis. GADM Level 2 provides the overall municipality boundary (used for filterBounds and clip), while GADM Level 3 provides 11 spatial units: 10 outer districts plus one combined central urban area encompassing the six inner districts that GADM aggregates into a single feature.






GAUL vs GADM for Chinese Cities



FAO/GAUL/2015/level2 filtered to ADM1_CODE == 899 returns only 2 features for Beijing — the dataset does not subdivide Chinese municipalities at the district level. GADM 4.1 Level 3, uploaded as a GEE Asset, provides 11 meaningful spatial units and was used for all per-district analysis. The GADM Level 2 union was used for the overall Beijing boundary to ensure spatial consistency.




2.2 Loading the Study Area Boundary
The Beijing boundary is derived from GADM Level 2 using .union() to merge all district polygons into a single municipality outline, and the 11 GADM Level 3 districts are loaded separately for per-unit analysis.


Show GEE code

//--------------------------Vector data---------------------------

var dataset = ee.FeatureCollection("FAO/GAUL/2015/level1");

var dataset_style = dataset.style({
  color: '1e90ff',
  width: 2,
  fillColor: '00000000',
});

Map.addLayer(dataset, {}, 'Second Level Administrative Units_1');

// Use GADM Level 2 for Beijing boundary — consistent with district-level data below
var gadm2 = ee.FeatureCollection('projects/week6-gee-coursework/assets/gadm41_CHN_2');
var Beijing = gadm2.filter(ee.Filter.eq('NAME_1', 'Beijing')).union();

Map.addLayer(Beijing, {}, 'Beijing');



2.3 Landsat 8 Land Surface Temperature
The thermal band ST_B10 records top-of-atmosphere brightness temperature in Kelvin; after applying the standard scale factor and subtracting 273.1, the result is surface temperature in Celsius. A cloud cover threshold of &lt; 10% is used — Beijing’s relatively dry summer climate makes this feasible, and the resulting 13 scenes provide adequate coverage.


Show GEE code

//--------------------------Landsat data---------------------------

function applyScaleFactors(image) {
  var opticalBands = image.select('SR_B.').multiply(0.0000275).add(-0.2);
  var thermalBands = image.select('ST_B.*').multiply(0.00341802).add(149.0);
  return image.addBands(opticalBands, null, true)
              .addBands(thermalBands, null, true);
}

var landsat = ee.ImageCollection('LANDSAT/LC08/C02/T1_L2')
  .filterDate('2022-01-01', '2022-10-10')
  .filter(ee.Filter.calendarRange(5, 9,'month'))
  .filterBounds(Beijing)
  .filter(ee.Filter.lt("CLOUD_COVER", 10))
  .map(applyScaleFactors);

print(landsat);

var subtracted = landsat.select('ST_B10').map(function (image) {
  var subtract = image.subtract(273.1);
  var mask = subtract.gt(0);
  var mask_0 = subtract.updateMask(mask);
  return mask_0;
});

var subtracted_mean = subtracted.reduce(ee.Reducer.mean())
  .clip(Beijing);

var vis_params = {
  min: 20,
  max: 55,
  palette: [
    '040274', '040281', '0502a3', '0502b8', '0502ce', '0502e6',
    '0602ff', '235cb1', '307ef3', '269db1', '30c8e2', '32d3ef',
    '3be285', '3ff38f', '86e26f', '3ae237', 'b5e22e', 'd6e21f',
    'fff705', 'ffd611', 'ffb613', 'ff8b13', 'ff6e08', 'ff500d',
    'ff0000', 'de0101', 'c21301', 'a71001', '911003'
  ]
};

Map.addLayer(subtracted_mean, vis_params, 'Landsat Temp');




Figure 1: Mean summer Land Surface Temperature (May–September 2022) derived from Landsat 8 ST_B10 over Beijing municipality. Higher temperatures (yellow–green) concentrate in the southern plains and the central urban core, while the mountainous northern and western districts (Huairou, Yanqing, Mentougou) remain markedly cooler (deep blue). Note that while the palette extends to red (max = 55°C), the maximum observed mean LST in Beijing stays within the green–yellow range (~35–38°C), confirming that extreme pixel-level temperatures are averaged out across the summer period.




2.4 MODIS Time Series and Per-District Analysis
With only 13 Landsat scenes available, temporal analysis is limited. MODIS compensates — merging Aqua (153 images) and Terra (153 images) gives 306 observations for the same period, enabling a meaningful temperature time series that reveals seasonal dynamics invisible to Landsat alone.


Show GEE code

//--------------------------MODIS (unscaled, for reference)---------------------------

var MODIS_Aqua_day = ee.ImageCollection('MODIS/061/MYD11A1')
  .filterDate('2022-01-01', '2022-10-10')
  .filter(ee.Filter.calendarRange(5, 9,'month'))
  .filterBounds(Beijing)
  .select('LST_Day_1km');

print(MODIS_Aqua_day, "MODIS_AQUA");

var MODIS_Terra_day = ee.ImageCollection('MODIS/061/MOD11A1')
  .filterDate('2022-01-01', '2022-10-10')
  .filter(ee.Filter.calendarRange(5, 9,'month'))
  .filterBounds(Beijing)
  .select('LST_Day_1km');

print(MODIS_Terra_day, "MODIS_Terra");

//--------------------------MODIS scaling---------------------------

function MODISscale(image) {
  var temp = image.select('LST_.*').multiply(0.02).subtract(273.1);
  return image.addBands(temp, null, true);
}

var MODIS_Aqua_day = ee.ImageCollection('MODIS/061/MYD11A1')
  .filterDate('2022-01-01', '2022-10-10')
  .filter(ee.Filter.calendarRange(5, 9,'month'))
  .select('LST_Day_1km')
  .map(MODISscale)
  .filterBounds(Beijing);

var MODIS_Terra_day = ee.ImageCollection('MODIS/061/MOD11A1')
  .filterDate('2022-01-01', '2022-10-10')
  .filter(ee.Filter.calendarRange(5, 9,'month'))
  .filterBounds(Beijing)
  .select('LST_Day_1km')
  .map(MODISscale);

//--------------------------MODIS mean image---------------------------

var landSurfaceTemperatureVis = {
  min: 15, max: 45,
  palette: [
    '040274', '040281', '0502a3', '0502b8', '0502ce', '0502e6',
    '0602ff', '235cb1', '307ef3', '269db1', '30c8e2', '32d3ef',
    '3be285', '3ff38f', '86e26f', '3ae237', 'b5e22e', 'd6e21f',
    'fff705', 'ffd611', 'ffb613', 'ff8b13', 'ff6e08', 'ff500d',
    'ff0000', 'de0101', 'c21301', 'a71001', '911003'
  ],
};

var mean_aqua_terra = MODIS_Aqua_day.merge(MODIS_Terra_day)
  .reduce(ee.Reducer.mean())
  .clip(Beijing);

Map.addLayer(mean_aqua_terra, landSurfaceTemperatureVis,
    'MODIS Land Surface Temperature');

//--------------------------Time series---------------------------

var aqua_terra = MODIS_Aqua_day.merge(MODIS_Terra_day);

var timeseries = ui.Chart.image.series({
  imageCollection: aqua_terra,
  region: Beijing,
  reducer: ee.Reducer.mean(),
  scale: 1000,
  xProperty: 'system:time_start'
}).setOptions({
  title: 'Temperature time series',
  vAxis: {title: 'LST Celsius'}
});
print(timeseries);




Figure 2: MODIS (Aqua + Terra merged) daily mean Land Surface Temperature time series for Beijing, May–September 2022. The 306 observations reveal clear seasonal structure: temperatures peak at approximately ~39°C in early June, followed by a sharp drop to around 15–16°C in late June coinciding with the onset of the main monsoon season (though, as discussed in Section 2.6, these extreme lows are heavily influenced by unmasked cloud cover rather than true surface cooling). A secondary warm spell (~37°C) is visible in mid-August before temperatures decline through September to approximately 25–30°C. This intra-seasonal variability would be entirely invisible with Landsat’s 16-day revisit.





Figure 3: Mean summer LST derived from merged MODIS Aqua and Terra collections (May–September 2022) at 1km resolution over Beijing municipality. The central urban core and southern plains show consistently higher temperatures (yellow–red), while the mountainous northern fringe remains cooler (blue–green) throughout the summer. Comparing this with Figure 1 (Landsat, 30m), both confirm the same macro-pattern — the urban core and Daxing are the warmest areas, the northern mountain districts the coolest. However, Landsat reveals finer spatial heterogeneity — individual roads, industrial zones, and water bodies are distinguishable — while MODIS smooths these out. This trade-off motivates using Landsat for the spatial heat index (Section 2.5) and MODIS for the temporal trend (Section 2.6).


For the per-district time series, I used seriesByRegion to plot a separate line for each administrative unit. With 11 GADM Level 3 districts and 306 merged Aqua+Terra images, the element count (11 × 306 = 3,366) stays within GEE’s 5,000 element limit, allowing the full merged dataset to be used.


Show GEE code

//--------------------------Statistics per level 2---------------------------

var gadm3 = ee.FeatureCollection('projects/week6-gee-coursework/assets/gadm41_CHN_3');
var Beijing_level2 = gadm3.filter(ee.Filter.eq('NAME_2', 'Beijing'));
print('Beijing spatial units:', Beijing_level2.size());
print('Unit names:', Beijing_level2.aggregate_array('NAME_3'));

Map.addLayer(Beijing_level2, {}, 'Second Level Administrative Units_2');

print(subtracted_mean);

var mean_Landsat_level2 = subtracted_mean.reduceRegions({
  collection: Beijing_level2,
  reducer: ee.Reducer.mean(),
  scale: 30,
});

Map.addLayer(mean_Landsat_level2, {}, 'mean_Landsat_level2');

Export.table.toDrive({
  collection: mean_Landsat_level2,
  description: 'mean_Landsat_level2',
  fileFormat: 'GeoJSON'
});

//--------------------------MODIS per spatial unit---------------------------

var timeseries_per_unit = ui.Chart.image.seriesByRegion({
  imageCollection: aqua_terra,
  regions: Beijing_level2,
  reducer: ee.Reducer.mean(),
  scale: 1000,
  seriesProperty: 'NAME_3',
  xProperty: 'system:time_start'
}).setOptions({
  title: 'Average temp per spatial unit',
  hAxis: {title: 'Date', titleTextStyle: {italic: false, bold: true}},
  vAxis: {
    title: 'LST Celsius',
    titleTextStyle: {italic: false, bold: true}
  },
  lineWidth: 1
});

print(timeseries_per_unit);

//--------------------------Export triplets CSV---------------------------

var triplets = aqua_terra.map(function(image) {
  return image.select('LST_Day_1km').reduceRegions({
    collection: Beijing_level2.select(['GID_3']),
    reducer: ee.Reducer.mean(),
    scale: 30
  }).filter(ee.Filter.neq('mean', null))
    .map(function(f) {
      return f.set('imageId', image.id());
    });
}).flatten();

print(triplets.first(), "trip");

Export.table.toDrive({
  collection: triplets,
  description: 'triplets_beijing',
  fileNamePrefix: 'triplets_beijing',
  fileFormat: 'CSV'
});




Figure 4: Daily MODIS LST per district across Beijing (Aqua + Terra merged, May–September 2022), with all 11 GADM Level 3 districts clearly labelled. The lines separate into two visible clusters: a warmer group (Daxing, Beijing central urban area, Shunyi, Fangshan) peaking at approximately 40–42°C in late May and early June, and a cooler mountain group (Huairou, Mentougou, Yanqing, Changping, Miyun, Pinggu) running consistently 5–8°C lower throughout the period. All districts register the sharp late-June temperature drop (some falling below 10°C) associated with monsoon cloud cover (see Section 2.6 on cloud contamination), and all show partial recovery in August before declining through September. The persistent spread between the two clusters throughout the summer confirms that the urban–rural thermal gradient is a structural feature of Beijing’s heat environment, not merely an artefact of a single hot day.








Why Export Triplets?



The triplets CSV — one row per (district, date, mean LST) — is the format needed for time series modelling in R. With 153 Aqua + 153 Terra images per district, there are sufficient observations to run a Mann-Kendall trend test and determine whether any district shows a statistically significant warming or cooling trend over the summer period.




2.5 Heat Index Classification in GEE and R
The final step classifies each district into a heat hazard level based on percentile rank of mean summer Landsat LST. This replicates the BBC heat vulnerability index methodology. I implemented this in both GEE and R to cross-check results.
One thing I noticed while doing this: the BBC method was originally designed for datasets with hundreds of spatial units (like UK postcodes or wards). Applied to Beijing’s 11 districts, the p99 threshold ends up isolating just a single district — which is mathematically fine but feels a bit blunt for only 11 units. A standard deviation-based classification might actually be more appropriate at this scale, though implementing that is a further step I didn’t take here.
When I cross-checked the GEE output against the R maps, the results didn’t match — four districts were showing as the lightest colour in GEE despite clearly having higher temperatures in R. After printing the mean values and percentile boundaries to the console, I found the cause: the classification code uses strict inequalities (.lt() and .gt()) throughout all conditions, meaning if a district’s mean LST falls exactly on a threshold value it doesn’t satisfy either side of the comparison and falls into the final else branch with percentile_cat = 0. With 11 districts this wasn’t a fringe case — Pinggu’s mean equalled p40 exactly, Shunyi equalled p70, Beijing equalled p90, and Daxing equalled p99, so 4 out of 11 districts were misclassified. The fix is to replace .gt() with .gte() for all lower-bound comparisons. This kind of bug would be invisible with hundreds of wards — the probability of any value hitting a threshold exactly approaches zero — but with only 11 features it broke nearly half the classification.

GEE Implementation


Show GEE code

//--------------------------Heat index (GEE)---------------------------

var percentiles = mean_Landsat_level2.reduceColumns({
  reducer: ee.Reducer.percentile([10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 60, 70, 80, 90, 99, 100]),
  selectors: ['mean']
});

print(percentiles, "percentile");

var p40  = ee.Number(percentiles.get('p40'));
var p70  = ee.Number(percentiles.get('p70'));
var p90  = ee.Number(percentiles.get('p90'));
var p99  = ee.Number(percentiles.get('p99'));
var p100 = ee.Number(percentiles.get('p100'));

print(p40, "p40");

var resub = mean_Landsat_level2.map(function(feat) {
  return ee.Algorithms.If(
    ee.Number(feat.get('mean')).lt(p40).and(ee.Number(feat.get('mean')).gt(0)),
    feat.set({'percentile_cat': 1}),
  ee.Algorithms.If(
    ee.Number(feat.get('mean')).gte(p40).and(ee.Number(feat.get('mean')).lt(p70)),
    feat.set({'percentile_cat': 2}),
  ee.Algorithms.If(
    ee.Number(feat.get('mean')).gte(p70).and(ee.Number(feat.get('mean')).lt(p90)),
    feat.set({'percentile_cat': 3}),
  ee.Algorithms.If(
    ee.Number(feat.get('mean')).gte(p90).and(ee.Number(feat.get('mean')).lt(p99)),
    feat.set({'percentile_cat': 4}),
  ee.Algorithms.If(
    ee.Number(feat.get('mean')).gte(p99),
    feat.set({'percentile_cat': 5}),
    feat.set({'percentile_cat': 0}))))));
});

var visParams_vec = {
  'palette': ['#fee5d9', '#fcae91', '#fb6a4a', '#de2d26', '#a50f15'],
  'min': 1,
  'max': 5,
  'opacity': 1.0,
};

var image = ee.Image().float().paint(resub, 'percentile_cat');

Map.addLayer(image, visParams_vec, 'Percentile_cat');

// Export Landsat LST raster for R interactive map
Export.image.toDrive({
  image: subtracted_mean,
  description: 'subtracted_mean',
  region: Beijing,
  scale: 30,
  fileFormat: 'GeoTIFF'
});




Figure 5: Heat hazard index by district across Beijing, classified into five percentile-based levels in GEE (after fixing the boundary condition bug — see text above). Daxing is at Level 5, the central urban core at Level 4, and the northern mountain districts (Huairou, Yanqing, Mentougou) at Levels 1–2, now fully consistent with the R output in Figure 7 and the spatial LST patterns in Figures 1 and 3.




R Implementation
The GeoJSON exported from GEE was loaded into R for independent heat index calculation and visualisation using tmap. The percentile breakpoints for Beijing’s 11 districts are: p40 = 32.04°C, p70 = 34.71°C, p90 = 36.34°C, p99 = 36.55°C — a relatively narrow range of ~7°C reflecting the mix of warm urban and cool mountain districts.


Show R code

library(tidyverse)
library(sf)
library(tmap)

# Read GeoJSON exported from GEE
temp &lt;- st_read("E:/Remote/week9/mean_Landsat_level2.geojson")

# Plot mean LST per district
tmap_mode("plot")
tm1 &lt;- tm_shape(temp) + 
  tm_polygons("mean", palette = "Reds") +
  tm_legend(show = TRUE) +
  tm_layout(frame = FALSE)
tm1

# Percentile rank function (from StackExchange)
perc.rank &lt;- function(x) trunc(rank(x))/length(x)

percentile &lt;- temp %&gt;% 
  mutate(percentile1 = (perc.rank(mean)) * 100) %&gt;%
  mutate(Level = case_when(
    between(percentile1, 0,  39.99) ~ "1",
    between(percentile1, 40, 69.99) ~ "2",
    between(percentile1, 70, 89.99) ~ "3",
    between(percentile1, 90, 98.99) ~ "4",
    between(percentile1, 99, 100)   ~ "5"
  ))

# Verify breakpoints
test &lt;- quantile(temp$mean, c(0.39999, 0.69999, 0.8999, 0.98999, 1.0))
print(test)

# Heat index static map
tm2 &lt;- tm_shape(percentile) + 
  tm_polygons("Level", palette = "Reds") +
  tm_legend(show = TRUE) +
  tm_layout(frame = FALSE)
tm2




Figure 6: Mean summer Landsat LST per district, Beijing (R/tmap). Daxing in the southern plain and the central urban core both record the highest mean temperatures (36–37°C range), while Huairou in the northeast mountains records the lowest (30.7°C). The spread of approximately 6°C is driven primarily by differences in elevation, land cover type, and impervious surface density.





Figure 7: Heat hazard index map produced in R using tmap, reproduced from the GeoJSON exported from GEE. Daxing is classified at Level 5, the central urban core at Level 4, and Tongzhou at Level 3–4, while the northern mountain districts (Yanqing, Huairou) sit at Level 1. This pattern is consistent with the mean LST map in Figure 6 — both Daxing’s flat agricultural plains and the dense impervious surfaces of the urban core drive high summer temperatures, just through different mechanisms. The percentile breakpoints computed in R (p40 = 32.04°C, p70 = 34.71°C, p90 = 36.34°C) confirm the distribution is narrow — all 11 districts fall within a ~7°C range — making the relative ranking the more policy-relevant metric rather than absolute temperature values.


The interactive map overlays the 30m Landsat LST raster with the district-level heat index polygons, allowing inspection of the correspondence between pixel-level temperature variation and the district-level classification.


Show R code — interactive map

library(terra)

temp_rast &lt;- rast("E:/Remote/week9/subtracted_mean.tif")

# Downsample to reduce file size for rendering
temp_rast_small &lt;- aggregate(temp_rast, fact = 4)

tmap_mode("view")

interactive &lt;- tm_shape(temp_rast_small) +
  tm_raster(col = "ST_B10_mean",
            col.scale = tm_scale_continuous(values = "brewer.reds")) + 
  tm_shape(percentile) + 
  tm_polygons(fill = "Level",
              fill.scale = tm_scale_categorical(values = "brewer.reds"),
              fill_alpha = 0.7) +
  tm_legend()

interactive

Figure 8: Interactive tmap view overlaying the Landsat LST raster (120m resampled) and the heat hazard district polygons at 70% opacity. This allows inspection of the correspondence between pixel-level temperature and the district-level classification.





2.6 Extended Analysis: Mann-Kendall Trend Test
I also ran a Mann-Kendall trend test on the MODIS triplets CSV to determine whether each district showed a statistically significant temperature trend over the May–September 2022 period.


Show R code

library(tidyverse)
library(Kendall)

triplets &lt;- read_csv("E:/Remote/week9/triplets_beijing.csv")

# Mann-Kendall per district
results &lt;- triplets %&gt;%
  group_by(GID_3) %&gt;%
  summarise(
    mk_tau = MannKendall(mean)$tau,
    mk_pval = MannKendall(mean)$sl
  )

# Join district names
name_lookup &lt;- percentile %&gt;% 
  st_drop_geometry() %&gt;%
  select(GID_3, NAME_3)

results_named &lt;- results %&gt;%
  left_join(name_lookup, by = "GID_3") %&gt;%
  select(NAME_3, GID_3, mk_tau, mk_pval)

print(results_named)

# LST distribution by district
triplets_named &lt;- triplets %&gt;%
  left_join(name_lookup, by = "GID_3")

ggplot(triplets_named, aes(x = NAME_3, y = mean, fill = NAME_3)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(x = "District", y = "LST (°C)", 
       title = "LST Distribution by Beijing District") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),
        legend.position = "none")

All 11 districts show a statistically significant negative tau (all p &lt; 0.001), indicating a consistent cooling trend across the summer period. This reflects the seasonal influence of the East Asian summer monsoon: temperatures peak in May–June then decline through July–August as monsoon rainfall increases cloud cover and reduces incoming solar radiation. Daxing shows the steepest decline (τ = −0.349), consistent with its low-lying plain location most exposed to monsoonal rainfall, while Yanqing shows the weakest trend (τ = −0.145), reflecting its more sheltered mountainous position.
That said, I should note that the monsoon season also brings heavy cloud cover, and I didn’t apply any QA bitmask cloud filtering to the MODIS data. This means some of those very sharp dips in the time series — particularly the drop to around 7°C visible in early June (Figure 2) — are almost certainly cloud contamination rather than real surface cooling. MODIS is an optical sensor and picks up cloud-top temperatures when thick cloud is present. A more rigorous approach would apply the MODIS QA band to mask cloudy pixels before computing the time series. I skipped that step to keep the workflow manageable, but it’s worth keeping in mind when interpreting the Mann-Kendall results — the negative tau values might partly reflect increasing cloud cover through the monsoon season rather than pure surface cooling.



Figure 9: Boxplot of daily MODIS LST distribution by Beijing district (May–September 2022). Beijing (central urban area) shows a high median (~32°C) with a compact IQR, reflecting consistent heat retention by dense impervious surfaces. Daxing records the most extreme high-temperature outliers (approaching ~45°C on individual days), consistent with its flat, low-albedo agricultural plains being particularly susceptible to intense daytime heating. The mountain districts — Huairou, Mentougou, and Yanqing — cluster at the lower end (~26–28°C median), confirming the persistent urban–rural thermal gradient observed in the spatial maps (Figures 1 and 3). Shunyi and Fangshan occupy a middle-to-warm position, reflecting their mixed peri-urban character.




2.7 Literature: Heat Justice and EO Evidence
(Wilson 2020) and (Li et al. 2022) both argue that heat maps only become policy-relevant when overlaid with socio-economic data — knowing where it is hot is less useful than knowing who is exposed there and why. (MacLachlan et al. 2021) provide a direct example in practice: using Landsat LST alongside green space and population density data to identify priority intervention zones in Perth, Australia. For Beijing, the heat index produced here (Figures 5 and 7) and the LST distribution (Figure 9) together show that Daxing (Level 5) and the central urban core (Level 4) consistently record the highest temperatures — Daxing through its flat, low-albedo agricultural plains, and the urban core through sheer density of impervious surface. Whether those areas also have lower green cover and higher population vulnerability is a question the analysis cannot yet answer, but it is exactly the kind of equity question that (Cardille et al. 2023) points towards.






Connecting Heat Index to Urban Policy



The Level 4–5 districts identified here — Daxing and the central urban core — could form the basis for targeted urban greening or heat emergency planning, though for very different reasons: Daxing needs more vegetation cover on its agricultural plains, while the urban core needs shade trees and cool surface materials in its dense street network. Overlaying this heat index with population density, elderly population share, and green cover data would transform a thermal map into a genuine vulnerability assessment.

2. Applications of the Content

2.1 Workshop: Loading the Study Area
I chose Chengdu as my study area — it has a really nice mix of land cover types all within one administrative boundary: dense urban core, flat agricultural plains, river corridors, and mountain-edge forest on the western fringe. That variety should make it an interesting case for classification. Loading the study area meant filtering the FAO GAUL Level 2 dataset by ADM2_CODE, which for Chengdu is 13255:


Show GEE code

// --------------------- Load vector data --------------------------------
var dataset = ee.FeatureCollection("FAO/GAUL/2015/level2");
var chengdu = dataset.filter('ADM2_CODE == 13255');

Map.setCenter(104.065, 30.659, 9);
Map.addLayer(chengdu, {color: '00909F', fillColor: '00000000', width: 2}, 'Chengdu boundary');

One thing worth noting is that ADM2_CODE is a numeric field — no quotes around 13255. Looking at Figure 2, the boundary is much larger than I expected. It covers not just the city proper but the surrounding counties under Chengdu’s administrative jurisdiction, including the mountainous northwest. This matters for classification because it means the study area includes both dense city and remote mountain terrain — quite different environments that the model needs to handle simultaneously.



Figure 2: Chengdu administrative boundary (ADM2_CODE = 13255) from FAO GAUL Level 2. The area extends well beyond the urban core into agricultural plains and mountain areas to the northwest — a much more diverse landscape than a pure “city” study might suggest.




2.2 Workshop: Two Approaches to Cloud Handling
Chengdu is famously cloudy — it sits in the Sichuan Basin and locals joke that you rarely see blue sky. This made the cloud handling step particularly important. The workshop offered two strategies, and I ran both to see what the difference actually looks like in practice.
Approach 1 — Low cloud cover threshold per tile:


Show GEE code

// --------------------- Approach 1: Low cloud cover --------------------------------
var divide10000 = function(image) {
  return image.divide(10000);
};

var wayone = ee.ImageCollection('COPERNICUS/S2_SR_HARMONIZED')
                  .filterDate('2022-01-01', '2022-10-31')
                  .filterBounds(chengdu)
                  .filter(ee.Filter.lt('CLOUDY_PIXEL_PERCENTAGE', 10));

var wayone_median = wayone.map(divide10000).median().clip(chengdu);

var visualization = {min: 0.0, max: 0.15, bands: ['B4', 'B3', 'B2']};
Map.addLayer(wayone_median, visualization, 'Way1: Low cloud filter');
print('Way1 image count:', wayone.size());

Approach 2 — Pixel-level cloud masking using QA60 bitmask:


Show GEE code

// --------------------- Approach 2: QA60 cloud mask --------------------------------
function maskS2clouds(image) {
  var qa = image.select('QA60');
  var cloudBitMask = 1 &lt;&lt; 10;   // Bit 10 = clouds
  var cirrusBitMask = 1 &lt;&lt; 11;  // Bit 11 = cirrus
  var mask = qa.bitwiseAnd(cloudBitMask).eq(0)
      .and(qa.bitwiseAnd(cirrusBitMask).eq(0));
  return image.updateMask(mask).divide(10000);
}

var waytwo = ee.ImageCollection('COPERNICUS/S2_SR_HARMONIZED')
                  .filterDate('2022-01-01', '2022-10-31')
                  .filterBounds(chengdu)
                  .filter(ee.Filter.lt('CLOUDY_PIXEL_PERCENTAGE', 20))
                  .map(maskS2clouds);

var waytwo_clip = waytwo.median().clip(chengdu);
Map.addLayer(waytwo_clip, visualization, 'Way2: QA60 mask + median');
print('Way2 image count:', waytwo.size());







Why Take the Median?



Even after pixel-level cloud masking, some artefacts remain. Taking the median across all images in the collection causes clouds — which have very high reflectance — to be pushed out of the middle of the distribution, leaving cleaner composite pixels (Cardille et al. 2023, chap. F2.1).








